NEWARK, March 1—A strike by employees of Transport of New Jersey, the state's largest bus company, was put off today at least until after midnight Friday morning.

The three‐day reprieve for 450,000 daily riders followed a 24‐hour extension of the strike deadline scheduled for 12:01 this morning.

Anthony Grazioso, a company spokesman, said, “We are very pleased with the announcement.” Officials of the 3,400 ‐ member Amalgamated Transit Union could not be reached for comment.

Transport of New Jersey operates in 20 of the state's 21 counties. It provides about 65 percent of the bus service within the state, 45 percent of the commuting bus service to New York, and about 80 percent of bus passenier transportation between New Jersey and Philadelphia.